'''Apoth''' is a term of endearment used by Northern [[England]]ers for a loved one who is labouring under the misapprehension they have done something to inadvertently cause consternation. 

Usually proceeded by ‘you daft’ or 'you silly', the term is designed to provide reassurance that whatever has caused the '''apoth''' to feel regretful is completely inconsequential and the '''apoth''' is very much loved:

'''Apoth''': “Ecky thump, I’m reet sorry, I feel like a prize pudding.”

Reassurer: “Come here, y’daft '''apoth'''. Dun’t matter a bit."

'''Apoth''': "Thanks luv. Now, can I get y'cuppa tea?"


According to the [http://0042bfe.netsolhost.com/dickshonary/ Blegburn Dickshonary], it derives from the area around [[Blackburn]], [[Lancashire]] and was in common usage in the late [[1800s]]. It is a contraction of ‘halfpenny’s worth’.